A striking petite young Asian woman stands in at a mountain top above a neon-lit metropolis, Red Incense Burner Summit in Hong Kong, where skyscrapers stretch into infinity. But this is no ordinary city. Reality itself shatters around her—buildings warp violently, twisting like snakes, and streets ripple as if the earth beneath them is liquid. Her body fractures into a cascade of glitching, electrified shards, each one showing a different version of herself: a warrior clad in glowing futuristic armor, a figure in traditional silk robes, another dissolving into swirling, vibrant geometric patterns. She walks forward, her every step sending shockwaves of energy rippling through the environment.
Her eyes blaze with wild, multicolored flames that shoot beams of light into the sky, tearing open a swirling, kaleidoscopic vortex. Colors bleed from the vortex, spilling like liquid fire, igniting the world in brilliant, pulsating hues. Giant, shimmering drones burst forth from this tear in the sky, flapping wings of molten gold and neon blue. They swarm around her, casting radiant shadows. Cars freeze mid-air, crumbling into pixels; people’s shadows warp and elongate, dragged into infinity. The city convulses, crumbling into a dazzling fusion of chaos and electric beauty, as if the digital world is consuming reality.
